<br>
Like the article says, it's not the game itself, it's the person. If you read the entire article, it says that a bunch of circumstances come together which triggered the event. It's not EQ itself, but it is a part of the problem. Yes you can be addicted to anything, but I know no one who eats 12 hours or more every day.<br>
<br>
They make a point of it that EQ is a haven for those who have no sex drive, are depressed, have low self esteem, etc. That is 100% correct in my opinion, because I was all of those things and became addicted easily. Don't blow this off so lightly. I know they are doing a very interesting study with that avatarsoffline program, and I wish them luck and I hope it turns out well. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/bthesafehouse.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=nenjindarkeyes>Nenjin Darkeyes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/1/02 11:50:23 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseoutsidenorrath.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6974.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Death of an EQ player - Mom blames the game</span><hr size=1> Great, pretty soon we will be seeing TV advertisements trying to keep kids &quot;Off the Evercrack&quot;.<br>
