<br>
It could have been worse.  He could have become addicted to crack cocaine and died a much less dignified death <not that shooting yourself is dignified, but better than ODing on the street somewhere>  Maybe EQ kept him alive longer than he would have been otherwise, maybe it gave him some happiness?  Who knows, clearly his family didn't communicate very well with him.<br>
<br>
Suicide is a horrible tragedy for those left behind, but blaming a video game for the feelings that led your loved one to take their own life is just grasping at straws.  There's probably a lot higher percentage of people that are well-adjusted <well, in a manner of speaking :P> that play EQ then there are people that don't have a life outside the game.  It's too bad that no one realized that he wasn't one of them.<br>
